            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Vargas\u2019s life has been an exercise in cataloging memories, a skill he learned long before earning his master\u2019s degree. The only child of a quiet Filipino nurse and a gregarious Basque-American baker, he grew up in Daly City, right on the foggy border of San Francisco. His childhood was a blend of two distinct cultures, defined by the scent of his mother's adobo and his father's sourdough. A reserved and observant boy, he was fascinated by his family\u2019s shoeboxes of fading photographs and letters, meticulously trying to piece together the narratives of relatives he\u2019d never met.\n\nHis path was solidified when his father passed away during his sophomore year at SF State. Tasked with sorting through a lifetime of belongings, Mateo felt the profound weight and importance of preservation. This experience transformed a casual interest into a calling. He pursued a graduate degree in Library and Information Science, specializing in the new frontier: digital preservation. He foresaw that the new shoeboxes were hard drives and cloud servers, and their contents were far more fragile. His career began at a university library, but he quickly moved into a role at a major city institution, becoming a Lead Archivist focused on preserving the Bay Area's ephemeral digital history\u2014from early dot-com websites to social media movements.\n\nNow 46, Mateo lives a life of contented routine in the Inner Richmond. His 2.5-mile MUNI ride to his SoMa office is a cherished ritual, a time for podcasts on history or tech ethics. He is thoughtfully single after a long-term relationship ended five years ago, finding solace in his small circle of friends, most of whom share his passion for obscure history or vintage electronics. His apartment is a quiet sanctuary filled with books and several disassembled mid-century radios he meticulously restores on weekends.\n\nMateo feels deeply connected to San Francisco's layered identity. He sees the city as a living document, from the Gold Rush architecture downtown to the digital ghosts of startups past. His dream is to secure funding for a definitive public archive of the city\u2019s digital subcultures. More personally, he hopes to one day take a long sabbatical to travel to both the Philippines and the Basque Country, to finally organize the most important archive of all: his own."
